    "\n",
    "### *Part 2: Linear Elastic Fracture Mechanics*\n",
    "\n",
    "#### *Task 1*\n",
    "\n",
    "Create maximum stress distribution and stress intensity plots away from a hole for a typical average stress level at 3 km depth (use information from the 1st set of exercises on Mohr-Coulomb) for this. Investigate what happens for different fracture geometries.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### *Solution:*\n",
    "\n",
    "**Step 1: Defining Boundary Conditions**\n",
    "\n",
    "Using stress levels from Part 1 (Task 3) at 3 km depth (uniform density scenario with ρ = 2650 kg/m³, ν = 0.25), we obtain the nominal applied stresses:\n",
    "- Vertical stress: $σ_v$ = ρgz = 2650 x 9.81 x 3000 / $10^6$ = 78 MPa\n",
    "- Horizontal stress: $σ_h$ = (0.25/0.75) × 78 MPa = 26 MPa\n",
    "\n",
    "For this analysis, we use the horizontal stress $σ_h$ = 26 MPa as the far-field nominal applied stress $σ₀$ acting perpendicular to the fracture orientation.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Step 2: Computing Stress Concentration Around Holes (Slides 8 & 9)**\n",
    "\n",
    "When a hole exists in a plate under stress, the stress field becomes disturbed near the hole. The stress concentration factor $K_t$ (Slide 8) quantifies how much the local stress is amplified compared to the far-field stress σ₀:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$K_t = \\frac{\\sigma_{max}}{\\sigma_0}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For elliptical holes with aspect ratio a/c where a is the half-major axis (in horizontal) and c is the half-minor axis (Slide 9), the maximum stress at the tip of the major axis is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\sigma_{max} = K_t \\cdot \\sigma_0$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where the stress concentration factor is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$K_t = 1 + 2\\left(\\frac{a}{c}\\right)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Three geometries investigated based on references in Slides 11 & 12:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Circular hole (a = c): $K_t$ = 3.\n",
    "2. Elliptical hole (a/c = 5): $K_t$ = 11.\n",
    "3. Sharp crack (c → 0): $K_t$ → ∞.\n",
    "\n",
    "In Slide 8, the stress concentration factor $K$ decreases with distance from the hole. At the hole edge (r = R), stress is maximum ($K_t$ × $σ₀$), but far from the hole (r >> R), stress returns to the undisturbed far-field value $σ₀$.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**Step 3: LEFM - Stress Intensity Factor for Sharp Cracks (Slide 18)**\n",
    "\n",
    "Circular and elliptical holes (analyzed in Step 2 using $K_t$) have finite stress concentration. For sharp cracks ($K_t$ = ∞) requires Linear Elastic Fracture Mechanics (LEFM) analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "For sharp cracks, we use the stress intensity factor $K_I$ to characterize the crack tip stress field. Slide 18 shows the stress distribution near a sharp crack tip follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\sigma_{y} = \\frac{K_I}{\\sqrt{2\\pi r}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Note:** According to Slide 18, the maximum stress is $\\sigma_y$ (perpendicular to crack plane) because this is the stress component that opens the crack in Mode I tension.\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $σ_y$ = stress perpendicular to crack plane (local stress field)\n",
    "- r = distance from crack tip\n",
    "- $K_I$ = stress intensity factor (MPa√m)\n",
    "\n",
    "The stress intensity factor $K_I$ depends on the applied stress $σ₀$ and crack geometry. For a through crack of half-length a under remote tensile stress:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$K_I = \\sigma_0 \\sqrt{\\pi a}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $\\sigma_0$ = nominal applied stress (far-field stress, MPa)\n",
    "- $a$ = crack half-length (m)\n",
    "- $K_I$ = stress intensity factor (MPa√m)\n",
    "\n",
    "To investigate different fracture geometries for sharp cracks, we analyze various crack half-lengths: a = 1 cm, 5 cm, 10 cm, and 50 cm.\n"
